               <interp inst="t18431127-282" type="date" value="18431127"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18431127-282-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-282-18431127 t18431127-282-offence-1 t18431127-282-verdict-1"></join>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18431127-282-charge-2" targOrder="Y" targets="def2-282-18431127 t18431127-282-offence-1 t18431127-282-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>282. <persName id="def1-282-18431127" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-282-18431127" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-282-18431127" type="age" value="20"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-282-18431127" type="surname" value="WESTWOOD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-282-18431127" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">JOHN WESTWOOD</hi>
                  </persName> and <persName id="def2-282-18431127" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def2-282-18431127" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-282-18431127" type="age" value="18"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-282-18431127" type="surname" value="ELLIS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-282-18431127" type="given" value="EDWARD"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">EDWARD ELLIS</hi>
                  </persName> were indicted for<rs id="t18431127-282-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18431127-282-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18431127-282-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="stealingFromMaster"></interp> stealing 2 saddles, value 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; 1 pair of reins, 4<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; 2 pair of trace, 1<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.; 1 pair of harness, 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; and 1 breeching, 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; the goods of <persName id="t18431127-name-1522" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1522" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1522" type="surname" value="CHEEK"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1522" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1522" type="occupation" value="bricklayer"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18431127-282-offence-1 t18431127-name-1522"></join>Joseph Cheek</persName> their master.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18431127-name-1523" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1523" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1523" type="surname" value="CHEEK"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1523" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>JOSEPH CHEEK</persName>
                  </hi>, <hi rend="italic">bricklayer, Commercial-road, Lambeth.</hi> I rent No. 11 arch of Waterloo-bridge, in which I keep horses and harness—the prisoners were in my employ—on Friday, the 10th of Nov., Westwood was employed at the arch all day to clean the harness—he had no business to remove any without orders—he left me on the 13th—I missed the things stated on the 12th—I saw the prisoners again in custody on the 18th, charged with taking the harness—they denied it—I have never seen it since.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. NEALE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Have you always given the same account of this? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; I swear I have never said that the prisoners left without giving me notice—I asked them on the Saturday when I paid them if they were satisfied—they said, "Yes"—I did not tell them I did not want them any more—I may have said that I missed the things on the 13th—I missed them on the 12th and 13th too, and on the 13th I sent to make inquiries about it—they were taken on the Friday—the arch is locked every night at eight o'clock, and another gate outside is locked—there is a regular watchman on the premises—I leave about eight o'clock—there is only one entrance—the other end is bricked up—I had six or seven men at that time—I have all their names in my book—they had been working with me about a month—the prisoners, I believe, worked the shortest—eight o'clock is the time for closing the vault—I was there about five o'clock on Friday evening, and told the prisoners to do them up—I came back and found Jeffreys and two others at work, but the prisoners were gone—I remained there about half an hour, seeing the work done—the harness that was taken hung up on the right hand as you go in—I keep horses and carriages there as well—when I left it at half-past six o'clock I left the door open, and left the men that were there and my son—he always stops to close the door—beyond the door are high outer gates, which are kept locked—a man named Griffin was in my employ, and worked for me a week after the prisoners left—he was at work on Friday the 10th—he comes at half-past seven o'dock, and stops till eight o'clock—I or my son are there to receive him, and take away the key—I always look round the place, lock it up, and take the key—it is my son's duty to look round as well as mine, but I do not look round on a Monday—most likely my son took the key home on the Friday—I saw it next morning at seven o'clock hanging on a nail by the fire-place in my front parlour—no one could get at it—I give it to the first that comes in the morning—I pay my men at my house every Saturday night—they do not come into the room where the key hangs, and I do not think they knew where it was kept—they were paid at the door—I never told Griffin I would give him two guineas if he would reveal the real thieves, nor was any sum mentioned by me or my wife in my presence—I never asked him to try and find the thieves—I dis<lb></lb>charged him last Saturday week, as he said he was going to drive for another person—I did not see him last Friday—I did not say any thing to Mr. Wise about the real thieves—I have not treated her—we had our dinner together—a man named Brown, who has worked for me on and off nearly two years, was working for me at the time of the robbery—I discharged him last Saturday—I have not seen him since—it was about two o'clock on Sunday the 12th that I went into the vault and missed the harness—I had not been there for three or four days—I did not then suspect the prisoners—I charged them with it on the Saturday following—I went to the nearest place, which</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184311270204"></xptr>
               <p>was Mr. Wise's—I thought tney drigfct nave seen persons go by with harness, and they stood for a while and thete said they did so on Friday evening—I have not accused any one else of this—there were more that I thought had some portion of it, but how I could not tell—I never accused them, because they absconded—one was Robertson—I cannot recollect the other's name—I did not employ the men regularly—I paid them on Saturday.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18431127-name-1524" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1524" type="gender" value="indeterminate"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1524" type="surname" value="JEFFREYS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1524" type="given" value="HENTRY"></interp>HENTRY JEFFREYS</persName>
                  </hi>. On the 10th of Nov. I was working for the prosecu<lb></lb>tor, at No. 11 arch, Waterloo-bridge—the prisoners were at work there, from six till half-past six o'clock—I saw them leave together—Ellis had two saddles, a breeching, and a pair of hames, on his left shoulder—Westwood assisted him in carrying them out—I saw them leave the arch with it—they did not come back—I was there till very near nine o'clock.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> How long have you been in the prosecutor's employ? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Twelve months—I went to work about seven o'clock on Friday morning I called at my master's house first for the key—he gave it to ne at the door—I generally call for it—if master is not up, I do not take it, but wait till he gires it me—I did not know where it was kept—the two prisoners were in the stable on Friday evening, when I returned at five o'clock—we all came in about five—master lets out <hi rend="italic">cabs</hi>—the two prisoners and two more men were at work—I remained there till they left, without going away—no one but us five were in the stable after five, except my master—his son came in with us—my master came about half-past five, and left—I did not see his son go with him, but I did not see him after master left—matter returned about half-past six, or a quarter to seven—the prisoners were then gone—no one but me was there—I did not tell my master or his son that the pri<lb></lb>soners had gone away with the harness—I we all three came away together—my syoung to master locked up the stable—master had then gone on about ten yards a-head—he could not have heard his son locking the door—this was from half-past eight till nice—when master left at half-past six, it was to see after see prisoners and the other men—I had to do their work—I did not know their names or addresses—I called them by nick-names, <hi rend="italic">Kingston Jack</hi> and <hi rend="italic">Fiddler</hi>—I gave the others no names—I cannot tell at what time theother men left—the last time I saw them was at five, when we all came back—I have not seen them since—the prisoners had no right to take the harness out of the stable, without they were told by master or his son—I did not hear them tell then to take it—master used to tell them to take it to his house, to be put away—it was new harness, and I thought they were going to take it to my master's—I told my master about it on the Sunday, when he spoke to me about it at the stable—before I worked for the prosecutor I worked for my father, who is a plumber, and drove vans—the harness used to be fetched back when it was wanted, and it was wanted on Sunday—I have heard nothing about a reward—I do not know Brown or Griffin—about nine men were employed about the stable on the Friday—the arch is fastened by a padlock—it was quite secure that night, and also in the morning—I never saw my young master, or any one, draw the staple when they went in, and push it in again.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> What light had you in the stable? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Four candles and large fire.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18431127-name-1525" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1525" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1525" type="surname" value="WISE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1525" type="given" value="SUSANNAH"></interp>SUSANNAH WISE</persName>
                  </hi>. I live in Commercial-road, Lambeth, very near the arches of Waterloo-bridge. About six o'clock on Friday evening, I saw Ellis with a saddle on his shoulder—he stopped and looked in my face, and I saw the curl on the side of his face—he was carrying harness—it was slipping, and Westwood went and helped it up—I was afraid of my winddw—I saw the brass of the harness—I can swear more to Ellis, because he came to my shop frequently, and the other not so often.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184311270205"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> How do you get your living? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> In a shop in the general line—my house is next door but one to the stable—I swear to Elliis, and have every reason to believe Westwood was the other man—I saw the side of his face, and it was nearly covered with the saddle—I have heard nothing of any reward—I have not been dining with or treated by Mr. Cheek to-day.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18431127-name-1526" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1526" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1526" type="surname" value="BROOK"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1526" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES BROOK</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">policeman.</hi>) I took Westwood, on the 18th, at Mr. Cheek's house—he said he knew nothing about it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18431127-name-1527" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1527" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1527" type="surname" value="GUEST"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-1527" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM GUEST</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">policeman.</hi>) I took Ellis on the 18th of Nov., and told him what for—he said he knew nothing at all about it—when he got a short distance from the house he ran away—I pursued and secured him—in taking him to the station he said others ought to be taken as well as him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CHEEK</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined.</hi> I went away twice—I went home to get my tea—I then came back and went away again—I was not there when the door was locked—the harness had not been taken home for the last fortnight—it was not taken home regularly, unless I ordered it.</p>
               <p>(The prisoners received good characters.)</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="largeCaps">WESTWOOD</hi>—<hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <rs id="t18431127-282-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
